<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1607144-as-a-teacher-i-wonder-if-i-can-read-this">As a teacher, I wonder if I can read this with mature 11th-graders, or whether it&#39;s too depressing/ heavy. Your thoughts? I know there was a response saying the book is ok for fifteen-year-olds, but in a (rather liberal) school setting?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1607144'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F178796.The_Good_Women_of_China">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1607144-as-a-teacher-i-wonder-if-i-can-read-this">2 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1607144-as-a-teacher-i-wonder-if-i-can-read-this">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/23009757-graham-brownett"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/23009757-graham-brownett">Graham Brownett</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">As a man I found the book depressing and enlightening. That it was written in the dark times before China started to open up gives an historical aspec<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">As a man I found the book depressing and enlightening. That it was written in the dark times before China started to open up gives an historical aspect to women's lives which mature students would now find incredible. There is much more to it than the individual stories, it is a chronicle of the life and times and the hardships that women suffered. I think your students would find it totally absorbing<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
