  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3748451820" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3748451820" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/126331285-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625213415p2/126331285.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3748451820?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/126331285-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126331285-emily?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126331285-emily?shelf=china">china</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126331285-emily?shelf=asia">asia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126331285-emily?shelf=emotional-af">emotional-af</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126331285-emily?shelf=in-translation">in-translation</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/126331285-emily?shelf=fav-non-fiction">fav-non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3748451820" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2525357746139209922">In 1989, what originally started as an evening radio show eventually turned into a platform for women to call in and share their stories of what it was like being a woman in China. The host of the radio show, Xue Xinran, later documented these stories and turned it into a book, &quot;The Good Women of China.&quot; Because these stories covered sensitive issues such as infanticide, forced marriage, political imprisonment, sexual assault, abuse, etc., Xinran had to leave China and publish the book in the UK</span>
  <span id="freeText2525357746139209922" style="display:none">In 1989, what originally started as an evening radio show eventually turned into a platform for women to call in and share their stories of what it was like being a woman in China. The host of the radio show, Xue Xinran, later documented these stories and turned it into a book, "The Good Women of China." Because these stories covered sensitive issues such as infanticide, forced marriage, political imprisonment, sexual assault, abuse, etc., Xinran had to leave China and publish the book in the UK.<br /><br />Having just finished the book, I can say without a doubt that this is one of the most depressing (and hardest) books I've ever read. The suffering and pain that these women went through simply because they were born female was unspeakable and horrific. There were times where I had to put the book down because of the amount of anger and frustration I felt; I wanted to go fight for these women and bring justice for them. Unfortunately, there was hardly a happy ending for these stories. This was the reality of women in China.<br /><br />I need to commend the author for not only writing so beautifully, but also at how brave, compassionate and empathetic she was. I don't know how she was able to hold it together after hearing these harrowing stories first hand, and then documenting them again into a book. My only gripe was that I wish we found out what happened to these women later - are they doing okay now? Are they at a better place now? While all of the stories were heartbreaking, the chapters that stood out to me the most were:<br /><br />1) The Girl Who Kept a Fly as a Pet<br />2) The Mothers Who Endured an Earthquake<br />3) The Woman Whos Father Does Not Know Her<br />4) The Women of Shouting Hill<br />5) The Guomindang General's Daughter<br /><br />Stories include women who are being raped by their own father and refusing to leave the hospital in fear of facing the abuse again. Girls being forced into marriages, being abandoned by a man who swore to love them forever, or losing their mind because of the amount of sexual abuse they suffered. I'm touched by every story in this book, and am reminded of how stunningly resilient and strong women are. While this book is a tragic and difficult read, it's an important one nonetheless. As noted in the book, "Everybody says women are like water. I think it's because water is the source of life, and it adapts itself to its environment. Like women, water also gives of itself wherever it goes to nurture life." </span>
  <a data-text-id="2525357746139209922" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

